<h1 class="hero-h">How to Prep for a Board Meeting with Claude <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">Get the deck right in half the time.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Board prep is high-stakes, high-time-cost work for CEOs. A well-built Claude workflow takes the synthesis off your plate so you can focus on the parts that actually need your judgment. Here's the workflow.</p>
<div class="tldr"><div class="tldr-l">Short answer</div><p class="tldr-p">Build a Board Prep Project loaded with past board decks, your KPI dashboard structure, and your board's specific concerns. Paste in this quarter's raw data + commentary; get a structured deck draft + narrative + likely Q&A list in 45 minutes. Always heavily edit before sending — board materials carry fiduciary weight.</p></div>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">The 4-step workflow</h2><ol class="ol"><li><strong>Set up the Project:</strong> Load 3-5 past board decks (good ones), your standing KPI structure, the strategic priorities from the last board meeting, and notes on each board member's specific concerns.</li><li><strong>Dump in this quarter's raw inputs:</strong> KPI numbers, ops updates, financial summary, customer wins/losses, hiring updates, strategic decisions needed.</li><li><strong>Use the prompt</strong> (below) to get a draft deck + speaker notes + Q&amp;A list.</li><li><strong>Heavily edit.</strong> Board materials must be in your voice, accurate to the dollar, and tuned to your specific board dynamic. Treat Claude's output as a first draft, never the final.</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Sample prompt</h2><p class="body"><strong>System prompt:</strong> "You are the Chief of Staff to the CEO of [Company]. Produce board-meeting materials in the structure of the example decks in your knowledge. Be ruthlessly concise. Flag anything you do not have data for. Output sections: 1) Executive summary (3 bullets), 2) KPI scorecard, 3) Key wins, 4) Key concerns, 5) Strategic decisions needed, 6) Likely board questions and suggested answers."</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">What to include in the dump</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Q's KPIs vs plan vs prior year (revenue, gross margin, ARR, CAC, retention, headcount, runway).</li><li>3-5 narrative bullets per function (sales, marketing, product, ops).</li><li>Significant customer events (large wins, churns, strategic accounts).</li><li>Hiring &amp; departures of note.</li><li>Strategic decisions you need board input or approval on.</li><li>Anything new that's happened since last board meeting they should know about.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">What to keep entirely human</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>The narrative on missed targets.</strong> Your judgment about why and what's next is the highest-stakes content in the deck. Write it yourself.</li><li><strong>Sensitive personnel discussions.</strong> Co-founder departures, exec changes, comp committee items. Never draft these with AI.</li><li><strong>Financial numbers.</strong> Pull from your accounting system, not from AI synthesis. AI can describe the numbers; it must not produce them.</li><li><strong>Strategic recommendations.</strong> The board hires the CEO for judgment, not for AI-mediated summaries. Own the recommendations.</li></ul></div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">FAQ</h2>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Will Claude know my board's concerns?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Only if you tell it. Maintain a Project knowledge file: per board member, what they care about, what frustrates them, what they always ask.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should I use Claude for the board pre-read?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Yes for the first draft. Heavily edit. The pre-read is often more important than the meeting; do not ship a first draft.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">How do I keep board materials confidential?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Use Claude Enterprise (or Team) with confirmed no-training settings. Never use personal Claude.ai or free ChatGPT for board materials.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Can Claude help me prep for Q&A?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Yes — strong use case. Ask Claude to play your most challenging board member and probe weak spots.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">How long should board prep take with this workflow?</h3><p class="faq-qa">First draft: 1 hour. Editing and judgment: 3-5 hours depending on stakes. Total ~half what unaided prep takes.</p></div>
</div></section>

